      </fr:frontmatter>
      <fr:mainmatter>
        <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" expanded="false" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:anchor>439</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">plt-languages-000B</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>plt-languages-000B.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Value">Value</fr:title>
            <fr:authors />
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>A <fr:em>value</fr:em> is a term that is fully reduced and cannot be reduced any further. Values
are the final results of computations.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>It is important to note that the word "value" is overloaded in programming language
theory. Syntactically and <fr:link type="local" href="plt-semantics-0003.xml" addr="plt-semantics-0003" title="Operational semantics">operationally</fr:link>, a value is a fully reduced
<fr:em>term</fr:em> in the syntactic domain characterized by an <fr:link type="local" href="plt-languages-000D.xml" addr="plt-languages-000D" title="Introduction form">introduction
form</fr:link> and an absence of <fr:link type="local" href="plt-languages-000E.xml" addr="plt-languages-000E" title="Elimination form">elimination forms</fr:link>.
Semantically and <fr:link type="local" href="plt-semantics-0002.xml" addr="plt-semantics-0002" title="Denotational semantics">denotationally</fr:link> speaking, a value is an object in
the model or the semantic domain of the language. Whereas operationally, the expression
<fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\text {add}(2, 3)]]></fr:tex> is different from the expression <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[5]]></fr:tex>, denotationally, they have the
same value, i.e., <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\llbracket  \text {add}(2, 3)\rrbracket  = \llbracket  5 \rrbracket ]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
      </fr:mainmatter>
      <fr:backmatter />
    </fr:tree>
  </fr:backmatter>
